solute_path.include?(File.expand_path(Pakyow::App.config.app.root))\r\n}\r\n      \r\nif modified_backtrace.empty?\r\n  # pakyow broke\r\nelse\r\n  relative_path = File.expand_path(Pakyow::App.config.app.root)\r\n  error.set_backtrace modified_backtrace.map { |l|\r\n    path = Pathname.new(l.absolute_path).relative_path_from(Pathname.new(relative_path))\r\n    \"#{path.to_s}:#{l.lineno}:#{l.label}\"\r\n  }\r\nend\r\n```\r\n\r\nNotice how if we never make it out of the framework code we present the full backtrace. I'd like to take this a step further and tell the user they found a bug, and ask them to report it. Let's be very clear so we don't leave them thinking they did something wrong.\r\n\r\n- [ ] Tell the user about errors that occur in the framework before hitting their code\r\n\r\nThis still needs to be done:\r\n\r\n- [ ] Start at the end of the backtrace and work forwards until we hit the application code, then include everything to the top. Right now any lines from a gem would be excluded.\r\n\r\n## Route Names\r\n\r\nAs part of this I would also like to present actual route names. Right now it looks like:\r\n\r\n```text\r\napp/lib/routes.rb:28:in `block in <class:FooRouter>'\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut I would like to see this:\r\n\r\n```text\r\napp/lib/routes.rb:28:in `GET / in <class:FooRouter>'\r\n```\r\n\r\nTo do this, we would need to get the details from the matched route and create our own label. We already have this state, so it should be doable.\r\n\r\n- [ ] Present the route name\r\n\r\n## Backtrace Formatting\r\n\r\nWhen using the development logger, the backtrace should be presented like this:\r\n\r\n```text\r\n  56.00s http.801ea89b | GET /foo (for ::1 at 2017-02-26 21:42:03 -0800)\r\n   3.48ms http.801ea89b | NameError: undefined local variable or method `f' for #<FooRouter:0x007ff775dc0e78>\r\n                        | app/lib/routes.rb:28:block in <class:FooRouter>\r\n   3.63ms http.801ea89b | 500 (Internal Server Error)\r\n```\r\n\r\n- [ ] Present th